<h2 id="lessons" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Key Takeaways</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside mt-2">
  <li><a href="#learned1" class="text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-200">Design Domain Ownership</a> gave us clear, separate responsibilities while maintaining our team roles.</li>
  <li><a href="#learned2" class="text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-200">Follow the Fun.</a> It’s natural for your ideas to change shape!</li>
  <li><a href="#learned3" class="text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-200">Design Requires Iteration</a> and dropping things that don’t work even if you’re attached to it.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="goals" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Design Goals</h2>
  <p>The main design goal we started with was to create a player who had free form movement balanced with more standard running and jumping mechanics to create a feeling of freedom.</p>

<h2 id="ownership" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Design Domain Ownership</h2>
<p class="mb-2">In the last two weeks of pre-production, we realized we were having trouble splitting up the responsibility of making design decisions. Based on advice from advisors, we decided to switch our design process to use Design Domain Ownership. Under Design Domain Ownership, team members take responsibility for specific domains of design, ensuring that related tasks are completed on schedule. It is up to the domain owner whether they do the tasks themselves or delegate to other team members; their job is to make sure design decisions happen before deadlines.</p>

<p>The design domains we identified are as follows:</p>
<ul class="ml-8 list-disc mb-4">
  <li>Player Abilities</li>
  <li>Obstacles and Threats</li>
  <li>Levels and Rooms</li>
  <li>Narrative and Dialogue</li>
  <li>UI/UX and Interfaces</li>
  <li>Art and Aesthertics</li>
  <li>Audio and Music</li>
</ul>

<p class="mb-2">Because Narrative, Art, and Audio are all asset-heavy domains, you can read more about their design processes here:
  <a class="text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-200" href="/games/art/">Art Page</a> --
  <a class="text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-200" href="/games/audio/">Audio Page</a> --
  <a class="text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-200" href="/games/narrative/">Narrative Page</a>
</p>

<p>You can read more about how we used design domain ownership here: <a target="_blank" class="text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-200" href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1IBiAL9DKJrxi6PZBs6QaPd42ccu7iJqAAUcAh5n113c/edit?tab=t.azn71u2r9gx3#heading=h.v32ddjjecv1k">Game Design Document</a></p>
{# LESSON 1 #}
<div class="mb-8 mt-8 rounded-lg p-2 border border-orange-200 dark:border-orange-800 bg-orange-100 dark:bg-orange-900/20 rounded-lg">
  <h3 id="learned1" class="font-semibold">Lesson 1: Design Domain Ownership</h3>
    <p class="ml-8">Once we established our domains, our trouble with splitting up responsibility disappeared, and we felt ready to tackle production as independent members of a cohesive team. Design domain ownership is a great way to split up responsibility and allow the team to focus on what design.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="design" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Design Domains</h2>
<p>Throughout production, we each did our part to iterate on each domain and bring them together as the game took shape. Let’s go over the major game design decisions of each domain and how we reached them.</p>
<h3 id="player" class="font-semibold mt-4">Player Abilities</h3>
<p>There were 3 levels of player design that we iterated through the process of making the game alongside the levels.</p>
<h4 class="mt-2">Iteration 1</h4>
  <p class="ml-8">The player had a resource meter which increased as the player moved with levels that required more precise control. The player base movements like running and jumping were clunky while leaf dashing and flinging, a small burst after exiting dash were well liked. </p>
<h4>Iteration 2</h4>
  <p class="ml-8">The resource meter remained the same but player movements were refined much more which highlighted how much chaining between the two modes with the fling was the real fun of our game.</p>
<h4>Iteration 3</h4>
  <p class="ml-8">The resource meter now came back when the player hit the ground allowing for more dynamic chaining and much shorter of just the player running or dashing. This allowed for much more coherent level design and a player that felt much more fun to control.</p>

{# LESSON 2 #}
<div class="mb-8 mt-8 rounded-lg p-2 border border-orange-200 dark:border-orange-800 bg-orange-100 dark:bg-orange-900/20 rounded-lg">
  <h3 id="learned2" class="font-semibold">Lesson 2: Follow the Fun</h3>
    <p class="ml-8">Throughout the design process we consistently iterated on our design to make the game more fun for players. We were always tweaking numbers, adjusting mechanics, watching what playtesters found the most fun, and going back to the drawing board to brainstorm new ideas.</p>
</div>

<h3 id="levels" class="font-semibold mt-4">Levels and Rooms</h3>
<p class="mb-2">Balancing gameplay and narrative was done by trying to ensure that between every narrative room there were at least  two gameplay levels. Because of how much iteration was required in terms of gameplay we had to cut down on the number of  levels as gameplay became more refined based on weekly playtests. We had to shift and follow the fun of the game and ended up almost completely changing the movement style of the player to fit new design pillars we had created as time went on.</p>

<p>To streamline level and room design, we utilized this spreadsheet to help track the status of each room.</p>
